args:
Harle reveals Cecile's crimes from her days as
a knight of Dyrenell. The guilt is overwhelming,
but Leif presses her to face herself and her own
code of justice, then challenges Harle to a
long-overdue duel.
In the name of Dyrenell's emperor, I bring\njudgment for dragonkind's crime of hubris.
Amazing as ever, ma'am. Even a dragon\nis as nothing before your blade.
This forest will burn ere long; my liege's\nwill is done here. Prepare to depart.
I hear Lector and Ronan have fallen.\nThat's two more towns for the list.
It was only a matter of time once Cecile\nslew their guardian dragon.
Without its dragon, the mana of a place\ngoes all out of whack. Water dries up,\nplants die... It turns into a wasteland.
Is that why she never burns an area\nafter she's subdued it?
Yeah, she must have concluded it would\nbe a waste of time and resources.\nThat's a smart leader right there.
(A knight cannot leave her regent's side,\neven if she must sully her hands with\nblood in their service.)
(If I'm to save the king, I must remain as\nclose to him as possible.)
(So long as I do, my chance will come.\nIt must!)
Stand aside, Harle! I'm going with\nHis Majesty!
You cannot. Only His Majesty and\nLady Zethia may enter this place.
Or will His Majesty's royal guard disobey\na direct order?
My place is at his side! My life exists only\nto protect his!
(My pulse is racing and my gut is one big\nknot... I know something will happen.)
If you insist on standing in my path, Harle,\nI will go to him over your corpse.
By the time I reached his side, His Majesty had\npassed. I was there—I was at his side—and yet\nI could do nothing to save him.
I had ended so many lives in the name of King\nAurelius's salvation, and for what? For nothing.
Aaaugh! Goddess forgive me! I've done\nsuch terrible things! Such horrid deeds!
Why do you weep, friend? You faithfully\nexecuted the orders of the king and then\nemperor whom you so dearly loved.
I never imagined you had a hand in the\ndragon purgings...
Is it so surprising a thought? I had a hand\nin the experiments to transform dragons\ninto fiends, myself.
Ah, but I suppose you wouldn't have known\nabout any of that after your demotion.
It's rude to snack during an important\nconversation, my dear. HAAAH!
You would defend her? This woman helped\nplunge the land you swore to protect into a\nworld of chaos and blood!

Though the results were hardly so grand a
thing as ＂chaos.＂ You went to all the effort
of slaying those dragons, and for what?
A few ruined towns and one dead king.
It would be tragic if it weren't so pathetic.

Do you honestly believe that a knight who
abandoned the path of good—a knight who
abandoned her solemn oath of fealty—
can truly start over?
You failed to uphold even one shred of\nyour ideals, but now dare think of serving\na new regent? Your hope is an affront.
He's right... I'm a failure... I can't do it...
I'm so sorry... Forgive me, Your Majesty,\nI...I beg you...  *sob*
Well, I doubt she'll be up and around\nanytime soon!
Templars, commence the operation.\nWipe out the White Sparrows waiting\npast these woods.
You have no say in this, boy. Haaah!
I would advise you to stay exactly where\nyou are, old friend.
Unless you want the blood of your man,\nthe hostages, and dear old Cecile on\nyour hands?
I'm sorry... I'm sorry... I'm sorry...\nI couldn't protect anyone... I'm so sorry...
Enough, Cecile. Blaming yourself will not\nchange what has already come to pass.
But it's the truth. I failed to protect him.\nI killed dragons...innocent people...
I couldn't uphold the ideals we spoke of;\nI couldn't even keep my own liege alive!\nFor all my talk, I've protected nothing!
You're wrong. There's something you have\nkept safe all this while.
That's not true! I have nothing left,\nthere's not—
Don't lose sight of yourself, Cecile!\nYou may try to deny it, but you have\npreserved one thing through all of this...
THAT'S your answer? THAT'S what you\nwant her to pin all of her hopes on?\nJustice? And HER justice, no less?
Bwaaah ha ha ha! Oh, but this is rich!\nI had no idea you were so wicked, Leif!
She slaughters dragons and civilians,\nleaves her king to die, and you stand\nthere and brand it JUSTICE?!
He's right... I have no claim to such\na thing...
Then why do you weep now?
You cannot abide evil. Is that not precisely\nwhy you suffer so?
No matter the wickedness of your past,\nthat spark of justice within you has never\ngone out. Never wavered.
It is because you wish to live justly that\nyou have struggled and anguished all this\ntime. It is why you seek to forget the past.
Your pain stands as proof of this.
A knight's last bastion is the justice within\ntheir own heart. So long as that stands,\nthey remain undefeated.
So my pain. My regret. My...
(If some scrap of justice does live on\ninside of me, does it mean I could walk\nthe knightly path once more?)
(And maybe even live up to my ideals?)
(Oh, to hell with what might be. People\nare counting on me NOW, and I intend to\nprotect them!)
Run, all of you! I'll hold them off!
Thank you, Leif. I feel like I can finally\nface myself again.
I can look into my heart and see that a\nknight's chivalry is still there!
Then I shall leave these men to you.
I won't let them harm these people.\nAnd as for you...
Yes, this is a task long since overdue.\nCome, Harle! Face me, if you dare!
Bwaaa ha ha! If this is how the two of you\nwant it, who am I to deny you?
As an old classmate, it will be my\npleasure to take your hollow, fragile\nsense of justice...
...And shatter it before your helpless eyes!
